[1] Global case numbers
Date: Mon 27 Dec 2021
Source: iNews [edited]
https://inews.co.uk/news/world/covid-cases-hit-record-numbers-in-france-and-italy-as-omicron-takes-hold-1371467


France, Italy and New York City have seen record numbers of COVID-19 cases over the Christmas holidays as the highly transmissible omicron variant has triggered a huge surge in infections worldwide.

France recorded 104 611 on [Sat 25 Dec 2021], according to data from the public health office, higher than the 94 124 infections the previous day and the first time the country has gone past 100 000 infections in a single day. The French government will meet on [Mon 27 Dec 2021] to discuss new restrictions to stem the increase. It comes after France announced earlier this month that all UK arrivals would be banned from entering the country unless they had a "compelling reason to do so".

The French government is also considering passing a law transforming its health pass needed to do some jobs and to go to cinemas and bars into a "vaccination" pass in the first half of January [2022]. The main aim of a vaccination pass will be to do away with the option of obtaining a valid certificate by testing negative instead of having the vaccine shots.

Italy saw the highest number of cases since the pandemic began on Christmas day, with 54 762 daily new cases, although the numbers dropped to 24 883 on [Sun 26 Dec 2021]. The iNews reported last week how the country, the first in Europe to be struck by the pandemic in February 2020, is now seeing a "pandemic of children" as 28% of the total reported cases were children.

Germany is set to bring in restrictions no later than the [Tue 28 Dec 2021] that will see limits on gatherings of 10 people. The country's Robert Koch Institute has also added the US, Spain, Portugal, Finland, Monaco and Cyprus to the high-risk travel list from Christmas Day, meaning those wanting to enter from those countries will be subject to extra requirements like a negative test result and quarantine on arrival which can be cut short with a negative test result.

In the US, New York state also recorded a record increase of 49 708 new COVID-19 cases on Christmas Eve, beating the record set one day earlier with 44 431 cases. The State Department of Health issued a warning claiming it had seen a 4-fold increase in children being admitted to hospital with COVID-19 since w/e [5 Dec 2021]. "The risks of COVID-19 for children are real," said acting state health commissioner Dr Mary T Bassett. "We are alerting New Yorkers to this recent striking increase in paediatric COVID-19 admissions so that paediatricians, parents and guardians can take urgent action to protect our youngest New Yorkers. We must use all available safe and effective infection control, prevention and mitigation strategies."

Elsewhere, Australia reported its first confirmed death from omicron amid its biggest daily surge in infections, but authorities refrained from imposing new restrictions saying hospitalisation rates remained low. The death - a man in his 80s with underlying health conditions - marked a grim milestone for the country which has had to reverse some parts of a staged reopening after nearly 2 years of stop-start lockdowns, due to the fresh outbreak.

The state of New South Wales recorded a record 6394 new coronavirus cases on Christmas Day [Sat 25 Dec 2021], according to health officials. State health minister Brad Hazzard said "we would expect that pretty well everybody in New South Wales at some point will get omicron. If we're all going to get omicron," he said, "the best way to face it is when we all have full vaccination, including our booster."

China's city of Xian has tightened rules and started a fresh round of testing on the 5th day its 13 million people are in lockdown. As the city reported 150 new local symptomatic coronavirus cases on [Sun 26 Dec 2021] a slight drop from the previous day's 155, lockdown rules have intensified, with only essential vehicles allowed on the streets. Since last week [w/e 26 Dec 2021], Xian residents have not been allowed to leave the city without permission from their employer or authorities. From [Mon 27 Dec 2021], no vehicles are allowed on the roads unless they are for virus control or for people's livelihoods and violators could face up to 10 days in police detention and 500 yuan fines.

Israeli Prime Minister Naftali Bennett started self-isolating on [Sun 26 Dec 2021] after his 14 year old daughter tested positive to COVID-19. He will now await a negative PCR result before resuming his activities. The premier's daughter had been vaccinated against the virus, his office said. It did not disclose whether she had been infected by omicron or the delta variant also prevalent in Israel.

It comes as a major hospital in Israel started administering 4th jabs after the government announced plans last week to roll out another booster for those aged 60 and over. The hospital will give the additional dose to 150 staff in a trial aimed at assessing whether a 2nd booster is needed nationwide to help protect people against omicron. Sheba Medical Centre near Tel Aviv said its trial would shed light on the efficacy of a 4th dose and help decision makers set health policy in Israel and abroad. Israel has reported 1118 confirmed cases of the fast-spreading omicron coronavirus variant, with the number of people infected by it doubling every 2 days.

[byline: Claire Gilbody-Dickerson]

